\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Assignment 9 Problem Two
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Cai
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
2.
 Find the limit of the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigg\{\sqrt{2},\sqrt{2\sqrt{2}},\sqrt{2\sqrt{2\sqrt{2}}}...\bigg\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I define the sequence with the recursive definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=\sqrt{2a_{n-1}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}a_{n}\rightarrow L$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, both 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 will approach the same limit 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 since one step should not make any difference in value when taking the
 limit to infinity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=\sqrt{2a_{n-1}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L=\sqrt{2L}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}=2L$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}-2L=0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L(L-2)=0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L=0,2$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=2$
\end_inset

 since obviously the infinite sum cannot equal 0.
 
\end_layout

\end_body
